Anonymous Mon 06 May 2019 02:22:49 No.22948816 Report
Quoted By: >>22949256
>>22944799
>best way to handle
>hybrids
Fertile or infertile, it really depends on the story and the world building for that story's setting. Is the story and the world building specifically to make some point about hybrids? The the "best" way is make sure the world building supports the point(s) of the story.

Does the world already exist for some story, and hybrids are some detail of the world building for that story?

Examples, consider Zootopia for one. That's a big world with all its own stories, but doesn't address hybrids. Only fanfictions have got into that (so far), and mainly to try and figure out if rabbits & foxes can have children or if they need to adopt or breed true to their species. Mules and such haven't been addressed, so there is interesting opportunity to incorporate that into the Zootopia world.

A different example is something like Two Kinds, where hybrids come in at least two forms. One main character was specifically bred from canine and feline stock as a slave for the pleasure of humans. Here's a direct genetic meddling/engineering that resulted in a sterile, sentient person who's pretty wrecked by how she was created and the fact that she can't have children. Yet, in the same world, species (humans and anthros) can actually interbreed on occasion. However, it's expressed as the children resemble one species or the other rather than a blend. And, a few rare ones can use magic to switch between the forms of their parents. Only possible because the world was built with magic.

An interesting "problem" arises that the author hasn't addressed (or seems to have even thought of). What happens several generations down the line when children from these pairing breed with children from other pairings? If one parent is descended form a cat-human couple and another from a wolf-human couple ... can this third or fourth generation child switch between all of these forms?

The "best" way is to think through your world building carefully.

Viruses mutate by incorporating DNA from other bacteria and viruses into their own. This is exactly where swine flu and avian flu viruses come from. There are things called phages that act sort of like parasites on viruses, and they can be one mechanism for transferring DNA and other genetic material by feeding on one virus and then infecting another.

Bacteria can jump between numerous species in different carrier methods. The Black Death is a bacterial infection carried by rodents and then transferred to other animals, such as humans. Commonly it is via flea bite or other intermediary parasite, but it can also be direct by blood or saliva, such as Ebola (to be clear, Ebola is a virus, not a bacteria). Other bacteria can be transferred by rodents defecating into/onto places that contaminate food and then people eat food that is contaminated.

There are hundreds of examples with many specific carrier methods.

tl;dr - Yes. Bacteria & viruses (and other parasites) can be transferred between anthros & humans & various species avian, fish, insect, mammal , etc. Make your you de-tick your waifur as well as use a condom. The diseases that can hop between species ted to be the nastiest varieties.
